4 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
5 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
6 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1330.1 of Title 74, unless there
7 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
8 As used in this act:
9 1. “Affiliate” means any person or entity that controls, is
10 controlled by, or is under common control with another person or
11 entity;
12 2. “Affiliated pharmacy” means any pharmacy, mail pharmacy,
13 specialty pharmacy, or pharmacy services provider that is owned,
14 operated, managed, or controlled by a pharmacy benefits manager
15 (PBM) or that otherwise shares profits or losses with the PBM or an
16 affiliate through common ownership, management, or contractual
17 arrangement;
18 3. “Control” means the possession of the power to direct or
19 cause the direction of management and policies of a person or
20 entity, whether through ownership of voting securities, by contract,
21 or otherwise. Control shall be established if a person or entity
22 owns, controls, or holds with power to vote, ten percent (10%) or
23 more of the voting securities or other ownership interest of the
24 other person or entity;
SB1447 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 4. “Operation data” means all data and records generated,
2 received, maintained, or derived in connection with the provision of
3 PBM services to a state plan, including claims data, pricing files,
4 payment and remittance data, adjudication edits, rejection and
5 reversal data, provider network files, pharmacy contracts and
6 amendments, audit records, formulary files, utilization management
7 outputs, communications affecting benefits, and any reports derived
8 from such data;
9 5. “Rebate” means any consideration or thing of value paid,
10 credited, earned, received, retained, or recovered from a
11 pharmaceutical manufacturer by a pharmacy benefits manager in
12 connection with the purchase, dispensing, coverage, placement,
13 administration, or utilization of a prescription drug or other
14 covered product for a person covered under the state plan,
15 regardless of how such consideration is characterized. Rebate
16 includes, but is not limited to, base rebates, formulary rebates,
17 incentive rebates, credits, price protection payments, market-share
18 incentives, promotional allowances, commissions, educational grants,
19 market-share utilization payments, drug pull-through programs,
20 implementation allowances, clinical detailing payments, rebate
21 submission fees, administrative fees, management fees, rebate
22 contracting fees, contract aggregation payments, and any other
23 similar payment or remuneration. Rebate does not include pharmacy
24
SB1447 HFLR Page 3
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 purc hase discounts and related service fees attributable to or based
2 on the purchase of drugs by specialty drug pharmacies;
3 6. “Remuneration” means anything of value, whether in cash or
4 in kind, paid, transferred, or provided to or for the benefit of a
5 PBM, or any affiliate or subcontractor of such PBM, in connection
6 with a prescription drug product or pharmacy benefit including, but
7 not limited to, rebates, discounts, price concessions,
8 administrative fees, services fees, data fees, network access fees,
9 market share fees, formulary placement fees, inflationary or price
10 protection payments, coupon or co-pay offset payments, dispensing or
11 transaction fees, reconciliation payments, and any other payments in
12 cash or credit regardless of characterization;
13 7. “State plan” means the self-insured plan provided pursuant
14 to the Oklahoma Employees Insurance Plan;
15 8. “Subcontractor” means any person or entity, other than an
16 employee of the PBM that performs, delegates, supports, or
17 administers any PBM function including claims processing, network
18 administration, rebate contracting or aggregation, formulary or
19 utilization management, mail or specialty pharmacy services,
20 auditing, pricing services, or data hosting, analytics, reporting,
21 or transmission whether under a written or oral agreement;
22 9. “Total net cost” means, for a stated measurement period, the
23 sum of all amounts paid by the state plan for covered prescription
24 drugs including, but not limited to, all ingredient cost amounts,
SB1447 HFLR Page 4
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 disp ensing fees, and any other amounts billed to the state plan and
2 all amounts paid by covered members for covered prescription drugs,
3 including co-payments, coinsurance, and deductible amounts, minus
4 all rebates and remuneration required to be passed through to the
5 state plan. Total net cost shall be calculated without regard to
6 the gross rebate volume or the list price of the drug; and
7 10. “Utilization management” means the same as defined in
8 Section 2562 of Title 63 of the Oklahoma Statutes.
9 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
10 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1330.2 of Title 74, unless there
11 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
12 A. Any pharmacy benefits manager (PBM) contract with a state
13 plan shall:
14 1. Declare state plan ownership of all plan-specific
15 operational data including, but not limited to, claims, pricing,
16 rebates, formulary, utilization management outputs, audit data, and
17 any such related reporting maintained by the PBM or any affiliate or
18 subcontractor of such PBM;
19 2. Provide that the state plan have broad audit rights and
20 shall determine designated auditors over any PBM and any affiliates
21 or subcontractors of such PBM to verify compliance with contract
22 provisions;
23
24
SB1447 HFLR Page 5
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 3. Establish network adequacy including rural access and
2 compliance with any applicable pharmacy choice and access rules
3 established by contract;
4 4. Provide that the state plan have exclusive authority over
5 formulary selection, tiering, preferred status, exclusions,
6 specialty designation, and utilization management of any provisions
7 of such contract. Nothing in this paragraph shall be construed to
8 prohibit the PBM from providing recommendations to the state plan
9 for formulary selection, tiering, preferred status, exclusions,
10 specialty designation, or utilization management; and
11 5. Offer for inclusion in such contract, at the election of the
12 state plan, one or more set pricing guarantee methodologies for
13 covered outpatient drugs including, but not limited to, National
14 Average Drug Acquisition Cost (NADAC) plus a dispensing fee, maximum
15 allowable cost (MAC) pricing, or any objectively verifiable
16 benchmark approved by the state plan.
17 B. No PBM shall:
18 1. Modify criteria, add restrictions, or change placement of
19 drugs on a formulary without written authorization by the state plan
20 to make such changes;
21 2. Restrict or prohibit the state plan from requiring or
22 negotiating set pricing guarantees;
23 3. Include any plan design or incentive to steer any members of
24 the state plan to a pharmacy affiliated with such PBM unless such
SB1447 HFLR Page 6
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 plan design or incentive is authorized in writing by the state plan
2 after submission of an impact analysis established pursuant to
3 subsection A of Section 3 of this act;
4 4. Establish network terms or reimbursement methodologies that
5 are less favorable to nonaffiliated pharmacies than to affiliated
6 pharmacies;
7 5. Establish gag clauses limiting the state plan’s ability to
8 share contract terms, performance metrics, audit results, or cost
9 data with oversight entities, auditors, actuaries, or counsel. Any
10 contract terms shared pursuant to this paragraph shall be subject to
11 reasonable confidentiality; and
12 6. Establish contract provisions that create reimbursement or
13 network conditions that exclude specific pharmacies from the network
14 without documented and state plan-approved access and cost
15 justifications.
16 C. The PBM shall be required to disclose any affiliates or
17 subcontractors of such PBM to the state plan prior to the awarding
18 of a contract and shall disclose any additional affiliate or
19 subcontractor at no fewer than thirty (30) days after such affiliate
20 or subcontractor is associated with the PBM.
21 D. All rebates shall be passed through to the state plan and
22 shall be subject to audit by the state plan, including inspection of
23 manufacturer rebate contracts without redaction. Nothing in this
24 subsection shall be construed to require the pass-through of any
SB1447 HFLR Page 7
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 amou nts authorized as fixed and separately stated administrative
2 fees to the state plan.
3 E. Any guarantees established by the contract between a PBM and
4 a state plan shall be determined by total net cost and access
5 outcomes and shall not be determined by rebate volume. Such
6 performance guarantees shall include clear remedies in the form of
7 credits payable by the plan for failure to comply with the
8 provisions of the contract.
9 F. A PBM shall:
10 1. Maintain System and Organization Controls (SOC) Type 2
11 certification for the duration of the contract with the state plan;
12 and
13 2. Provide to the state plan, all plan-specific operational
14 data and reporting in the form and medium prescribed by the plan
15 within the time frame established by the contract, or if not
16 specified, within five (5) business days of the state plan’s request
17 for then existing data, and within thirty (30) days after the close
18 of each month for monthly files and reports. Such PBM shall not
19 withhold or delay such data or charge any amount except for the
20 fixed administrative fee for extraction, access, interfaces,
21 licensing, or delivery, including any fees imposed by affiliates or
22 subcontractors of such PBM, and shall remain responsible for
23 compliance even if such data is held or processed by such affiliate
24 or subcontractor.
SB1447 HFLR Page 8
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1330.3 of Title 74, unless there
3 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 A. The pharmacy benefits manager (PBM) shall provide a written
5 impact analysis to the state plan prior to the state plan approving
6 any change to contract provisions, formularies, utilization
7 management criteria, network design, reimbursement methodologies, or
8 any plan design or incentive pursuant to paragraph 3 of subsection B
9 of Section 2 of this act. No change shall be implemented unless the
10 state plan authorizes in writing such change. Such impact analysis
11 shall include at minimum:
12 1. The total number of members impacted by each proposed
13 change;
14 2. The total net plan cost impact of each proposed change;
15 3. The member out-of-pocket impact of each proposed change;
16 4. The state plan cost impact of each proposed change; and
17 5. The pharmacy access impact of each proposed change,
18 including rural access impacts.
19 B. The PBM shall submit an electronic report in a form and
20 medium prescribed by the state plan that shall include for each
21 prescription drug claim itemized, claim-level reporting data
22 sufficient to validate the following:
23 1. The date of dispensing;
24 2. The National Drug Code (NDC);
SB1447 HFLR Page 9
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 3. The drug quantity;
2 4. The number of days’ supply;
3 5. The dispensing pharmacy identifier in the form of the
4 National Provider Identifier (NPI) and the National Council for
5 Prescription Drug Programs (NCPDP) Number;
6 6. If the dispensing pharmacy is affiliated with the PBM;
7 7. The final total payment received by the dispensing pharmacy
8 from all sources;
9 8. The ingredient cost paid to the dispensing pharmacy;
10 9. The final dispensing fee paid to the dispensing pharmacy;
11 10. Any post-adjudication fees, withholds, recoupments,
12 incentives, or other adjustments applied to the claim;
13 11. The total gross amount billed to the state plan for the
14 claim;
15 12. The total gross amount billed to the state plan for the
16 drug’s ingredient cost;
17 13. The total gross amount billed to the state plan for the
18 dispensing fee;
19 14. The total net amount billed to the state plan for the
20 claim;
21 15. The total net amount billed to the state plan for the
22 drug’s ingredient cost;
23 16. The total net amount billed to the state plan for the
24 dispensing fee; and
SB1447 HFLR Page 10
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 17. All other amounts charged in connection with the claim.
2 C. Any contract term in violation of the provisions of this act
3 shall be voidable and severable at the election of the state plan.
4 Any violation of the provisions of this act may constitute a
5 material breach and may be grounds for termination for cause, in
6 addition to any other remedies available under contract or law.
7 D. Any request for proposal for PBM services for the state plan
8 shall include:
9 1. Bidder certification of compliance;
10 2. A compliance narrative; and
11 3. Sample contract language demonstrating compliance with the
12 provisions of this act.
13 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
14 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1330.4 of Title 74, unless there
15 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
16 In evaluating proposals for a contract between a pharmacy
17 benefits manager (PBM) and the state plan, the state plan may assign
18 favorable scoring or weighting to proposals based on factors in
19 addition to price including, but not limited to:
20 1. Accessibility and in-state presence, including the ability
21 of the PBM to provide regular in-person meetings with state
22 officials and the positive economic impact of the PBM’s operations
23 within this state, including employment, investment, and other
24 economic activity within this state;
SB1447 HFLR Page 11
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 2. Compliance history, including the PBM’s record of regulatory
2 actions, legal judgments, settlements, or enforcement actions
3 involving a state, self-insured plan, or governmental entity
4 relating to pharmacy reimbursement, claims processing, audit
5 practices, or other PBM business activities; and
6 3. Transparent pricing models, including the offering of a
7 flat-fee-per-claim-processed model or a per-member-per-month
8 administrative fee model that minimizes or eliminates spread pricing
9 and other undisclosed revenue streams.
10 SECTION 5. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
